/*Data for the table `statistics` */

insert  into `statistics`(`Disease_ID`,`Disease_Name`,`World_stats`,`Bangladesh_stats`) values 
(1,'Diabetes','I can provide you with a general overview of global diabetes statistics up to my knowledge cutoff date in September 2021. However, I don\'t have access to real-time data or data beyond that date. To obtain the most up-to-date and accurate global diabetes statistics for the year 2022, I recommend referring to reputable sources like the World Health Organization (WHO) or the International Diabetes Federation (IDF).\r\n\r\nHere are some key global diabetes statistics and trends up to 2021:\r\n\r\n1. **Prevalence:** The prevalence of diabetes has been steadily increasing worldwide over the years. In 1980, the estimated global prevalence of diabetes was around 4.7%, affecting approximately 108 million adults. By 2021, the number of people living with diabetes had risen to over 400 million, with a global prevalence of around 8.5%.\r\n\r\n2. **Type 1 vs. Type 2:** The majority of diabetes cases are type 2 diabetes, which is strongly linked to lifestyle factors such as obesity, poor diet, and physical inactivity. Type 1 diabetes, an autoimmune condition, accounts for a smaller percentage of cases.\r\n\r\n3. **Regional Variation:** Diabetes prevalence varies by region. Some regions, such as the Middle East, North America, and certain parts of Asia, have higher rates of diabetes. Meanwhile, some countries in Africa have lower prevalence rates.\r\n\r\n4. **Complications:** Diabetes can lead to various complications if not well managed, including cardiovascular disease, kidney disease, neuropathy, retinopathy (eye problems), and foot ulcers. These complications contribute significantly to healthcare costs and mortality.\r\n\r\n5. **Impact on Health Systems:** The rising prevalence of diabetes places a substantial burden on healthcare systems globally due to increased healthcare costs, hospitalizations, and the need for ongoing management and treatment.\r\n\r\n6. **Risk Factors:** Common risk factors for type 2 diabetes include obesity, sedentary lifestyle, unhealthy diet, genetics, and age. Early detection and prevention efforts are essential in addressing the diabetes epidemic.\r\n\r\nIt\'s important to note that the global diabetes situation may have evolved since my last update in September 2021. Therefore, for the most recent and accurate statistics on diabetes worldwide in 2022, I recommend consulting authoritative sources like the World Health Organization (WHO), the International Diabetes Federation (IDF), or national health agencies. They often publish comprehensive reports and data on diabetes prevalence, management, and associated trends.','I can provide a general overview of diabetes in Bangladesh up to my last knowledge update in September 2021. However, please keep in mind that specific and up-to-date statistics for the year 2022 may not be available. For the most recent and accurate data on diabetes in Bangladesh for 2022, I recommend consulting sources like the Bangladesh Ministry of Health and Family Welfare or international health organizations like the World Health Organization (WHO).\r\n\r\nHere are some key points regarding diabetes in Bangladesh up to 2021:\r\n\r\n1. **Prevalence:** Diabetes has been on the rise in Bangladesh, primarily due to lifestyle changes, urbanization, and an aging population. The prevalence of diabetes in Bangladesh has increased significantly over the years. In 1980, the prevalence was relatively low, but by 2021, it had reached approximately 10-12% of the adult population.\r\n\r\n2. **Type 2 Diabetes:** Type 2 diabetes is the most common form of diabetes in Bangladesh, accounting for the majority of cases. It is often associated with obesity, poor diet, physical inactivity, and genetics.\r\n\r\n3. **Urban-Rural Disparities:** Diabetes rates tend to be higher in urban areas of Bangladesh compared to rural areas. This disparity is partly attributed to changes in lifestyle and diet associated with urbanization.\r\n\r\n4. **Complications:** Diabetes-related complications, such as cardiovascular disease, kidney disease, and eye problems, are a growing concern in Bangladesh. These complications contribute to healthcare costs and morbidity.\r\n\r\n5. **Diabetes Awareness and Healthcare:** Efforts to increase awareness about diabetes and improve healthcare services for diabetes management have been ongoing in Bangladesh. Initiatives include diabetes education programs, awareness campaigns, and the expansion of healthcare facilities for diabetes care.\r\n\r\n6. **Government Initiatives:** The Bangladesh government has recognized the importance of addressing the diabetes epidemic and has taken steps to develop and implement policies and programs aimed at diabetes prevention, diagnosis, and management.\r\n\r\n7. **Access to Medication and Treatment:** Access to diabetes medications and treatment can be a challenge in some parts of Bangladesh, particularly in rural areas. Efforts have been made to improve access to essential medications and healthcare services.\r\n\r\nPlease note that the situation regarding diabetes in Bangladesh may have evolved since my last update in September 2021. For the most recent and detailed statistics on diabetes in Bangladesh in 2022, I recommend referring to official reports and publications from relevant health authorities and organizations within Bangladesh.'),
(2,'Blood pressure','I don\'t have access to real-time data or the ability to provide specific statistics beyond my knowledge cutoff date in September 2021. However, I can provide you with a general overview of global trends in blood pressure based on data available up to that point. Please note that for the most up-to-date and detailed statistics on blood pressure trends from 1980 to 2022, you should consult reputable sources like the World Health Organization (WHO), the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), or academic studies and reports.\r\n\r\n1. **Global Prevalence of Hypertension**:\r\n   - Hypertension (high blood pressure) is a significant global health concern.\r\n   - The prevalence of hypertension has been steadily increasing over the years due to various factors, including aging populations, dietary changes, and sedentary lifestyles.\r\n   - It is estimated that over 1 billion people worldwide had hypertension as of the early 2020s.\r\n\r\n2. **Regional Variation**:\r\n   - The prevalence of hypertension varies significantly by region. Some regions, such as parts of Asia and Africa, have higher rates of hypertension.\r\n   - Lifestyle factors, genetics, and healthcare access contribute to these regional variations.\r\n\r\n3. **Impact on Health**:\r\n   - Hypertension is a major risk factor for cardiovascular diseases, including heart disease and stroke, which are leading causes of death globally.\r\n   - It can also contribute to other health problems, including kidney disease and vision problems.\r\n\r\n4. **Awareness and Control Rates**:\r\n   - Global awareness of hypertension has been increasing, with more people becoming aware of their condition and seeking medical care.\r\n   - However, the control of hypertension remains a challenge, with many individuals not achieving target blood pressure levels despite treatment.\r\n\r\n5. **Impact of COVID-19**:\r\n   - The COVID-19 pandemic had a significant impact on healthcare systems and access to medical care, which may have affected the management of chronic conditions like hypertension.\r\n   - Some reports suggest that stress and lifestyle changes during the pandemic may have influenced blood pressure levels.\r\n\r\n6. **Interventions and Guidelines**:\r\n   - Various organizations, including the WHO, have issued guidelines for the prevention, diagnosis, and management of hypertension.\r\n   - These guidelines emphasize lifestyle modifications, early detection, and appropriate treatment to reduce the burden of hypertension and its associated health risks.\r\n\r\nTo obtain precise and up-to-date statistics on blood pressure trends from 1980 to 2022, I recommend consulting authoritative sources like the WHO\'s Global Health Observatory, the CDC\'s National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES) reports, or academic research publications. These sources provide comprehensive and regularly updated data on hypertension and related health trends.','I apologize, but I do not have access to specific country-level statistical data on blood pressure trends for Bangladesh from 1980 to 2022. To obtain detailed and up-to-date statistics on blood pressure trends in Bangladesh over this period, I recommend consulting reputable sources such as:\r\n\r\n1. **World Health Organization (WHO)**: The WHO often publishes reports and data on the health status of countries, including information on hypertension and blood pressure trends.\r\n\r\n2. **Bangladesh Bureau of Statistics (BBS)**: The BBS may have data related to health and disease prevalence in Bangladesh, which could include information on blood pressure trends.\r\n\r\n3. **Academic Research and Studies**: Academic institutions and researchers may have conducted studies and surveys related to blood pressure and cardiovascular health in Bangladesh.\r\n\r\n4. **National Health Surveys**: Bangladesh may conduct national health surveys that include data on blood pressure and related health indicators.\r\n\r\n5. **Health Ministries and Government Reports**: The Ministry of Health and Family Welfare in Bangladesh may have reports and data related to hypertension and public health initiatives.\r\n\r\nTo access specific data on blood pressure trends in Bangladesh for the requested period, it\'s advisable to contact relevant government agencies, research institutions, or organizations that specialize in public health data collection and analysis. They can provide you with the most accurate and up-to-date information.'),
(3,'Influenza_or_flu','I don\'t have access to real-time or updated statistical data beyond my last knowledge update in September 2021. To provide a worldwide statistical overview of influenza from 1980 to 2022, I would need access to current and historical data sources, which I do not have. Influenza data is typically collected, compiled, and reported by organizations like the World Health Organization (WHO) and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in the United States, among others.\r\n\r\nFor up-to-date and accurate information on influenza statistics, including trends, outbreaks, and vaccination coverage, I recommend consulting official sources like the WHO, CDC, or relevant national health agencies. They regularly publish reports and provide access to historical data on influenza and other infectious diseases. You can also refer to academic research articles and publications for more in-depth analysis of influenza trends over the years.','I\'m unable to provide real-time or updated statistical data, and my knowledge only extends up until September 2021. To obtain a detailed statistical overview of influenza (flu) in Bangladesh from 1980 to 2022, you would need to consult official sources such as the Bangladesh Ministry of Health and Family Welfare, the World Health Organization (WHO), or other relevant health agencies and organizations.\r\n\r\nThese entities typically collect, analyze, and publish data related to infectious diseases like influenza, including the number of cases, seasonal variations, vaccination coverage, and more. They may provide historical data and reports that offer insights into the prevalence and impact of the flu in Bangladesh over the specified time frame.\r\n\r\nI recommend visiting the official websites of these organizations or contacting them directly for access to the most up-to-date and comprehensive influenza statistics for Bangladesh. Additionally, academic institutions and research organizations may also conduct studies and publish reports on influenza trends in specific regions, including Bangladesh.'),
(4,'Allergy','I don\'t have access to real-time or specific worldwide statistics on allergies from 1980 to 2022. Additionally, my knowledge is based on information available up to September 2021. Gathering comprehensive and up-to-date global allergy statistics would require access to databases and reports from various health organizations and research institutions.\r\n\r\nHowever, I can provide some general insights into the trends and factors related to allergies during this period:\r\n\r\n1. **Increased Prevalence**: Allergies have been on the rise globally since the late 20th century. This includes conditions like allergic rhinitis (hay fever), asthma, food allergies, and atopic dermatitis (eczema).\r\n\r\n2. **Geographic Variations**: The prevalence of allergies varies by region and can be influenced by factors such as climate, environmental allergens, genetics, and lifestyle. Western countries, in particular, have seen higher rates of allergies.\r\n\r\n3. **Environmental Factors**: Changes in environmental factors, including increased pollution, urbanization, and changes in diet, have been associated with the rise in allergies.\r\n\r\n4. **Food Allergies**: Food allergies, especially in children, have seen a significant increase. Common allergenic foods like peanuts, tree nuts, and shellfish have been a focus of research and public health efforts.\r\n\r\n5. **Asthma**: Asthma, often triggered by allergies, has also seen an increase in prevalence. Efforts have been made to improve asthma management and reduce the burden of the disease.\r\n\r\n6. **Research and Awareness**: Over this period, there has been substantial research into the causes and treatments of allergies, as well as an increase in public awareness of allergies and anaphylaxis.\r\n\r\n7. **Allergen-Specific Immunotherapy**: Advances have been made in allergen-specific immunotherapy (allergy shots and sublingual immunotherapy) as a treatment option for certain allergies.\r\n\r\nTo obtain precise and up-to-date statistics on allergies, you may refer to reports and publications from organizations like the World Allergy Organization (WAO), the World Health Organization (WHO), and national health agencies in various countries. These organizations often conduct surveys and compile data on allergy prevalence and trends. Additionally, academic research studies and medical journals may provide more detailed insights into specific aspects of allergies during the specified time frame.','I\'m sorry, but I do not have access to specific allergy statistics for Bangladesh from 1980 to 2022. Access to such detailed and up-to-date country-specific statistics would require data from healthcare organizations, government agencies, and research institutions in Bangladesh.\r\n\r\nTo obtain specific allergy statistics for Bangladesh during this time period, you may consider the following steps:\r\n\r\n1. **National Health Surveys**: Check if the Bangladesh government or health organizations have conducted national health surveys or studies that include data on allergy prevalence and trends. These surveys often provide valuable insights into the health of the population.\r\n\r\n2. **Research Papers**: Look for research papers and studies published by universities, medical institutions, and research organizations in Bangladesh. These studies may contain allergy-related data and trends specific to the country.\r\n\r\n3. **Government Health Agencies**: Contact government health agencies in Bangladesh, such as the Directorate General of Health Services (DGHS), and inquire if they have collected and published data on allergies.\r\n\r\n4. **Medical Associations**: Reach out to medical associations or allergy specialist groups in Bangladesh. They may have access to allergy-related data and resources.\r\n\r\n5. **Global Health Organizations**: Consult international health organizations like the World Health Organization (WHO) or the World Allergy Organization (WAO). They may have data on allergy trends in various countries, including Bangladesh.\r\n\r\n6. **Academic Institutions**: Contact universities or academic institutions in Bangladesh that have departments or research centers focused on allergies or immunology. They may have conducted studies or gathered data on allergies.\r\n\r\n7. **Public Health Reports**: Check for public health reports and publications issued by the Bangladesh government or relevant health authorities. These reports often include data on various health conditions, including allergies.\r\n\r\nIt\'s important to ensure that any statistics or data you obtain are reliable and up-to-date. Additionally, consider the specific types of allergies you are interested in (e.g., respiratory allergies, food allergies) and whether you are looking for prevalence rates, treatment patterns, or other specific information related to allergies in Bangladesh.');

/*Table structure for table `tools` */

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS `tools`;

CREATE TABLE `tools` (
  `ToolID` int(100) DEFAULT NULL,
  `ToolName` varchar(600) DEFAULT NULL,
  `Description` text DEFAULT NULL,
  `Disease` varchar(600) DEFAULT NULL
) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4 COLLATE=utf8mb4_general_ci;

/*Data for the table `tools` */

insert  into `tools`(`ToolID`,`ToolName`,`Description`,`Disease`) values 
(1,'Insulin Syringes','Insulin is typically U-100 strength and can be administered 1-4 times daily. It can be injected using a syringe or an insulin pen, which can be prefilled or have an insertable cartridge. ','Diabetes'),
(2,'Insulin Pens','An insulin pen is an injection device with a needle that delivers insulin into the subcutaneous tissue.','Diabetes'),
(3,'Insulin Pump','Insulin pumps are small and it is connected to a thin tube known as a catheter, which you put under your skin with a needle.The catheter regularly delivers insulin from the pump in small doses that are programmed and vary throughout the day and night.','Diabetes'),
(4,'Glucometer','Known as a blood glucose meter or a glucometer, is a portable electronic device that measures your blood sugar to make sure it\'s not too high or too low.','Diabetes'),
(5,'Ketone Test Strips','Ketone test strips are used to measure the presence of ketones in urine,often used by people with diabetes to monitor ketone levels.','Diabetes'),
(6,'Sphygmomanometer','A sphygmomanometer is a medical device used to measure blood pressure. It typically consists of an inflatable cuff to temporarily stop the blood flow, a mercury or mechanical manometer to measure the pressure, and a means of inflating the cuff. ','Blood pressure'),
(7,'Thermometer','Used to monitor body temperature, which can help detect fever, a common symptom of the flu.','Influenza'),
(8,'Pulse Oximeter','To monitor oxygen saturation levels, as respiratory complications can arise from severe cases of the flu.','Influenza'),
(9,'IV Fluids','In cases of severe dehydration due to the flu, intravenous fluids may be necessary.','Influenza'),
(10,'Skin prick test kit','This is used to diagnose allergic conditions by testing the skin\'s reaction to different allergens.','Allergy'),
(11,'Peak Flow Meter',' This measures how well air moves out of the lungs, which can be helpful in diagnosing and managing allergic respiratory conditions such as asthma.','Allergy'),
(12,'Epinephrine Auto-injector','Essential for individuals with severe allergies, especially those at risk of anaphylactic shock, as it can provide rapid treatment in case of a severe allergic reaction.\r\n','Allergy'),
(NULL,'sfgsd','adgd','Allergy');

/*Table structure for table `workout` */

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS `workout`;

CREATE TABLE `workout` (
  `id` int(11) NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
  `Name` varchar(100) DEFAULT NULL,
  `exercise` text DEFAULT NULL,
  PRIMARY KEY (`id`)
) ENGINE=InnoDB AUTO_INCREMENT=12 DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4 COLLATE=utf8mb4_general_ci;

/*Data for the table `workout` */

insert  into `workout`(`id`,`Name`,`exercise`) values 
(1,'Diabetes','1. Walking :\r\n\r\nWalking is a low-impact activity that many people enjoy. Getting your steps can improve your blood pressure, glucose, and cholesterol levels. And 30 minutes of brisk walking or about 100 steps a minute is a great way to meet the ADA\'s recommendation for daily aerobic exercise. \r\n\r\n2. Running :\r\n\r\nWith proper training and your healthcare provider\'s approval you can work your way up from brisk walking to running. This faster-paced activity has been linked to a reduced risk of high blood pressure, high blood sugar, and high cholesterol. \r\n\r\n3. Yoga :\r\n\r\nYoga involves low-impact movement, meditation, and breathing. It can improve balance, flexibility, and strength. This is especially helpful for older people with T2D who might be at greater risk of falling. The practice may also help you manage your blood sugar and cholesterol levels. '),
(2,'Heart','1. Aerobic Exercise : \r\n\r\nAerobic exercise improves circulation, which results in lowered blood pressure and heart rate. In addition, it increases your overall aerobic fitness, as measured by a treadmill test, for example, and it helps your cardiac output (how well your heart pumps). Aerobic exercise also reduces the risk of type 2 diabetes and, if you already live with diabetes, helps you control your blood glucose.\r\n\r\nIdeally, at least 30 minutes a day, at least five days a week.\r\n\r\n2. Resistance Training : \r\n\r\nResistance training has a more specific effect on body composition, Stewart says. For people who are carrying a lot of body fat (including a big belly, which is a risk factor for heart disease), it can help reduce fat and create leaner muscle mass. Research shows that a combination of aerobic exercise and resistance work may help raise HDL (good) cholesterol and lower LDL (bad) cholesterol.\r\n\r\nAt least two nonconsecutive days per week of resistance training is a good rule of thumb, according to the American College of Sports Medicine.');

